## Scope

This slice builds the optical table and the top‑down rendering geometry as
pure, headless‑testable projections, plus the standardized control flavours.
It adds `Table.fs` (the plate record + view state), `Drawer.fs` (the single
standard cylinder drawer keyed by kind + value id), `ConstructorTable.fs`
(top‑down layout geometry + ray drawing weights), and `Controls.fs` (the one
control‑flavours module). It extends the project aggregate and schema with
the table, and proves drawer geometry, the active‑element indicator
threshold, the CR‑only default, control‑flavour usage, and the table
round‑trip headlessly.

The existing `Schematic.fs` (a vertical cross‑section view, Schematic.fs:18)
MUST NOT be repurposed or removed; the top‑down surface is net‑new. The
FuncUI `Canvas` binding (the only Avalonia‑aware seam) and the MVU page that
hosts it are delivered with the interaction model in slice 005; this slice
delivers only the pure geometry and the controls.

## Requirements

### R-1. The plate (C.1)

C.1.1 A new module `Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Domain/Table.fs`
MUST define an `OpticalTable` record holding the plate's physical width,
length, and thickness in canonical meters, plus a display unit. The default
size MUST be `1.2 m × 2.0 m × 0.10 m` (width × length × thickness).

C.1.2 The plate size MUST be editable by the user and MUST be stored with
the project (A.8.2), so a reopened experiment shows the same plate.

C.1.3 The plate MUST be drawn as a grey plate to scale, so elements and
beams sit at true relative scale.

### R-2. View state: pan, zoom, rotate, reset defaults (C.2)

C.2.1 The default view MUST be top‑down. `Table.fs` / `ConstructorTable.fs`
MUST carry the view state (the table's own R1/R2/R3 measured relative to the
screen, pan offset, zoom) with the default view being straight top‑down
`(0, 0, 0)` and a sensible default zoom.

*(The pan/zoom/rotate/reset interaction gestures and their bindings, and
table selection on click, are wired by slice 005 — AC‑C2 and AC‑C3 are owned
there. This slice owns the default top‑down view state and the reset target
`(0, 0, 0)` + default zoom as pure values, per C.2.1 and C.2.5.)*

### R-3. The drawer (C.4)

C.4.1 A new module
`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/Drawer.fs` MUST define
the drawer as a pure function whose inputs are the element's placement
point, its three rotations, its **element kind**, and its **element value
id** (`None` for the first build), returning pure top‑down draw geometry
(no Avalonia type). Passing the kind and the value id explicitly from the
start is mandatory so per‑role and (later) per‑device/material looks can be
added without rewiring placement or ray logic.

C.4.2 For the first build there MUST be exactly **one standard drawer** used
by every element, drawing the element as a **cylinder**: a visible cylinder
frame with a very light‑grey, transparent interior so rays passing through
remain visible. Two role‑based shadings MUST depart from that default: the
light source is drawn in a darker shade; the detector is drawn almost
black, but with its frame still visible so it can be seen and selected.

C.4.3 The drawer MUST offer a **show / hide bounding box** option, off by
default. When on, the box edges MUST make R1/R2/R3 visible at a glance for
inspecting an element's orientation.

### R-4. Drawing weights (schematic conventions) (C.5)

C.5.1 The schematic MUST follow established optics ray‑diagram practice:
the central ray is the prominent line (the chief‑ray analogue) and the side
rays are lighter (marginal‑ray analogue). There is no formal standard for
pixel weights, so the following concrete defaults are fixed here (see
References) and MUST be named constants so a single edit restyles the
schematic:
- central ray: 2.0 px, solid, full opacity;
- side rays: 1.0 px, solid, ~60% opacity;
- reflected group: same hue as the transmitted group at ~35% opacity (it
  carries less energy), so reflected and transmitted read apart at a
  glance;
- element cylinder frame: 1.0 px outline; interior fill light‑grey at ~15%
  opacity;
- grid lines (if drawn): 1.0 px at ≤25% opacity, so the grid never competes
  with geometry.

C.5.2 Colours MUST be chosen for clear on‑screen visibility and MUST be
expressed as pure colour values the FuncUI binding maps to Avalonia, in the
same style as `SchematicColor` (Schematic.fs:35).

### R-5. Active‑element clarity (C.6)

C.6.1 The active element MUST be drawn so that it is unmistakably the active
one (a highlight / halo / selection frame). The active‑element indicator
MUST be at least 2 px and contrast at least 3:1 against the table
background (WCAG focus‑indicator floor; see References). Acting on the wrong
element silently is the main hazard, so this clarity is a firm requirement,
not a nicety. The exact treatment is a design detail; the clarity is not.

### R-6. Show central ray only, or all rays (C.7)

C.7.1 The constructor MUST offer an option to show only the CR or the CR
together with all eight side rays. The default MUST be CR‑only (most
reasoning is on the CR alone; side rays are switched on for focusing or
dispersion). This toggle MUST live on the *Trace / View* ribbon (Part D)
and MUST redraw the table when changed.

*(The ribbon control that hosts the toggle is wired by slice 006; this
slice owns the CR‑only default state and the redraw‑on‑change geometry.)*

### R-7. Reuse before invention for the surface (C.8)

Reuse `SchematicColor` (Schematic.fs:35) as the colour value shape. Do not
fold the top‑down table geometry into `Schematic.fs` (a different,
cross‑section view); add the new `Table.fs` / `Drawer.fs` / top‑down layout
modules instead.

### R-8. Single control‑flavours module (J.1)

J.1.1 A new module
`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/Controls.fs` MUST be the
single place that describes the standard control flavours: a default button,
a primary/accent button, a destructive button, a toggle, and a
numeric‑field‑with‑units. Each flavour MUST be a function the call sites use
instead of styling buttons ad hoc.

J.1.2 When a new flavour is genuinely needed (e.g. a differently coloured
button to stand out), it MUST be added in `Controls.fs` by changing only the
minimum set of properties that distinguish it, rather than styled at the
call site. This is consistency and one‑touch restyling, not a comprehensive
design system.

### R-9. Reuse before invention for controls (J.2)

The new constructor views MUST use `Controls.fs` flavours. The existing
`positiveCta`/`negativeCta` (ConstructionView.fs:40) MUST be expressed as
the destructive‑gate flavour in `Controls.fs` so the same‑row Confirm/Cancel
gate (UX commitments) draws from one definition.

## Non-requirements

- No FuncUI `Canvas` MVU page and no interaction gestures (pan/zoom/rotate
  selection, drag) — owned by slice 005 (Part E). AC‑C2 and AC‑C3 are owned
  there.
- No ribbon controls (the *Trace / View* toggle host, the table‑resize
  control) — owned by slice 006 (Part D).
- No repurposing or removal of `Schematic.fs` (C.0).
- No caching / retained‑mode scene graph / drawing‑backend abstraction (0.6).

